<paper id="1736584826"><title>Counting classes: thresholds, parity, mods, and fewness</title><year>1990</year><authors><author org="Department of Computer Science, P.O. Box 2158, Yale Station, New Haven, CT 06520-2158, USA" id="2310185924">Richard Beigel</author><author org="Stanford, University" id="2111762186">John Gill</author><author org="Universität Würzburg, Am Hubland" id="349845525">Ulrich Hertrampf</author></authors><n_citation>114</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1565875822</reference><reference>1967283546</reference><reference>1975784724</reference><reference>1982406523</reference><reference>1986804393</reference><reference>1989159237</reference><reference>2002323159</reference><reference>2006912660</reference><reference>2007464118</reference><reference>2029980187</reference><reference>2033323875</reference><reference>2041317738</reference><reference>2044504659</reference><reference>2051378572</reference><reference>2057512592</reference><reference>2059442002</reference><reference>2065251436</reference><reference>2070678975</reference><reference>2078999165</reference><reference>2094404282</reference><reference>2125536734</reference><reference>2163323474</reference><reference>2987475227</reference></references><venue id="1178070762" type="C">Symposium on Theoretical Aspects of Computer Science</venue><doi>10.1016/0304-3975(92)90084-S</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.53009">Complexity class</keyword><keyword weight="0.45498">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.45244">Combinatorics</keyword><keyword weight="0.46163">Closure (mathematics)</keyword><keyword weight="0.45857">Oracle</keyword><keyword weight="0.61298">#P-complete</keyword><keyword weight="0.40388">Philosophy of language</keyword><keyword weight="0.52919">Turing machine</keyword><keyword weight="0.5155">Time complexity</keyword><keyword weight="0.40319">Parity (mathematics)</keyword><keyword weight="0.41175">Mathematics</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Counting classes are classes of languages defined in terms of the number of accepting computations of non-deterministic polynomial-time Turing machines. Well known examples of counting classes are NP, co-NP, ⊕P, and PP. Every counting class consists of languages in P#P[1], the class of languages computable in polynomial time using a single call to an oracle capable of determining the number of accepting paths of an NP machine.</abstract></paper>